3ï¸âƒ£ Writing my First Python Program
Create a new Python file (hello.py) and write:
print("Hello, World!")
Run the script using:
python hello.py
Output:
Hello, World!

4ï¸âƒ£ Python Syntax & Basics
ğŸ”¹ Indentation (No {} like C/C++)
Python uses indentation instead of curly brackets {} to define code blocks.

ğŸ”¹ Comments
Single-line comment:
# This is a comment

Multi-line comment:
"""
This is a multi-line comment
written in Python.
"""
ğŸ”¹ Printing Output
print("Welcome to Python!")
Multiple values can be printed using commas:
name = "Alice"
age = 25
print("My name is", name, "and I am", age, "years old.")
Output:
My name is Alice and I am 25 years old.

5ï¸âƒ£ Python Data Types
ğŸ”¹ Common Data Types
Data Type	Example	Description
int	x = 10	Whole numbers
float	y = 3.14	Decimal numbers
str	name = "Python"	Text
bool	is_valid = True	Boolean values (True/False)
ğŸ”¹ Checking Data Types
Use type() to check variable types:
x = 10
y = 3.14
name = "Python"
print(type(x))   # Output: <class 'int'>
print(type(y))   # Output: <class 'float'>
print(type(name))  # Output: <class 'str'>
ğŸ”¹ Type Conversion (Casting)
Conversion between different data types:
a = "100"  
b = int(a)  # Convert string to integer  
print(b)  # Output: 100

Practice questions:

ğŸ“problem1.py (Print Your Name)
# Printing my name
print("My name is Niharika.")

ğŸ“ problem2.py (Simple Calculator)
# Taking user input
num1 = int(input("Enter first number: "))
num2 = int(input("Enter second number: "))
# Calculating sum
sum_result = num1 + num2
# Printing the result
print("Sum:", sum_result)

ğŸ“ problem3.py (Check Data Types)
# Taking user input
num = input("Enter a number: ")
text = input("Enter a string: ")
# Checking data types
print("Data type of", num, "is", type(num))
print("Data type of", text, "is", type(text))
# Converting num to int
num = int(num)
print("Data type after conversion:", type(num))

ğŸ“ problem4.py (Temperature Converter)
# Taking temperature input
celsius = float(input("Enter temperature in Celsius: "))
# Converting to Fahrenheit
fahrenheit = (celsius * 9/5) + 32
# Printing the result
print("Temperature in Fahrenheit:", fahrenheit, "Â°F")

ğŸ“ problem5.py (Swap Two Numbers Without Using a Temporary Variable)
# Taking input from the user
a = int(input("Enter first number: "))
b = int(input("Enter second number: "))
# Swapping numbers
a, b = b, a
# Printing results
print("After swapping:")
print("First number:", a)
print("Second number:", b)

